				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.gwen-morse.com/wiki/index.php/Linux">Back to Linux</a>
</p>
<h1><span class="mw-headline" id="DDO_on_Gentoo_Linux">DDO on Gentoo Linux</span></h1>
<p>One game I particularly enjoy playing is Dungeons and Dragons Online. I focus my attention on the Sarlona and Orien servers.
</p><p>I've been working on some <a href="/wiki/index.php/Tips_for_DDO_Noobs" title="Tips for DDO Noobs">Tips for DDO Noobs</a>.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Installing_DDO">Installing DDO</span></h2>
<p>No matter which version of wine you use to run DDO, you'll want a stable launcher. The native windows DDO launcher may or may not work depending on the code base and phase of the moon. The python launcher: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://github.com/Lynx3d/pylotro">pyloro launcher</a> should always work.
</p><p>In Crossover Linux use the existing Crosstie.
</p><p>I've switched my DDO install from Crossover to basic Wine. This allows me to eliminate any issues that may be caused by Crossover fixes that don't properly work.
</p><p><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://appdb.winehq.org/objectManager.php?sClass=application&amp;iId=2910">Official WineHQ Page for DDO</a>
</p><p>For vanilla Wine on Gentoo distributions:
</p><p>Make sure to get all the 32 bit wine packages, gnutls, and store Winetricks somewhere useful:
</p>
<pre>
emerge wine
emerge -DuN gnutls
wget http://winetricks.org/winetricks
</pre>
<p>gnults is needed to make the store browser function correctly.
</p><p>Make sure your wine bottle is 32-bit (needed if you're on a 64-bit system). It's very important to delete any existing .wine directory before running winearch.
</p>
<pre>
rm -rf .wine
WINEARCH=win32 WINEPREFIX=~/.wine winecfg
</pre>
<p>Then, pre-install the Windows packages needed for DDO to run. The tahoma font is to reduce issues with the awesonium wrapper. Physx is only needed for nVidia video cards:
</p>
<pre>
bash ./winetricks vcrun20{03,05,08,10} d3dx9 corefonts tahoma physx
</pre>
<p>Once you're sure the .wine directory is set up and waiting, you can install DDO:
</p>
<pre>
wine dndsetup.exe
</pre>
<p>And build PyLOTRO from source...
</p><p>To set the correct video memory size
</p>
<pre>
winetricks videomemorysize=1024 (stealth)
 or
winetricks videomemorysize=512 (cowspot)
</pre>
<p>If sound is crackling badly and you haven't disabled Pulseaudio, use this in your ~/.bashrc:
</p>
<pre>
alias wine='PULSE_LATENCY_MSEC=60 wine' (wine)
 or
PULSE_LATENCY_MSEC=60 (crossover)
</pre>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Specific_Fixes">Specific Fixes</span></h2>
<p>Crash Problem: crashing with an error indicating direct X 9.0c isn't installed - OpenGL issues - reinstall nVidia driver
</p><p>No sound: use winecfg to update the libaries to include openal32.dll, Windows native version.
</p><p>Exceptionally Bad Persistant Static: If you have functional sound without using the Windows native openal32, try removing it to clear up any static.
</p><p>alt-tab crashes client: in the bottle un-set "Allow the window manager to control the windows" and set "emulate a virtual desktop". 
</p><p>On cowspot, my desktop resolution is 1920x1200.
</p><p>On stealth, my desktop resolution is 1920x1080.
</p><p>Secondary Sound issue: Using either Crossover or vanilla Wine, DDO cannot share sound with another application (like Mangler, the Ventrilo client). This means I either get audio chat streams in DDO or I get audio chat in Mangler program). The stated fix for this is to change to the wine ALSA drivers. Directions on how to do this in Vanilla Wine found here: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://askubuntu.com/questions/77210/how-to-change-the-default-audio-in-wine-to-alsa-only">Change Default Audio To Alsa in Winetricks </a>
</p><p>Other crashing (Awesonium and other issues) discussed here: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://appdb.winehq.org/objectManager.php?sClass=version&amp;iId=28606">WineHQ Database entry for DDO Update 18.3 </a>
</p><p>If the client gives messages about needing to install Visual C runtime, or just hangs badly on the launcher, you may want to manually install the Visual C redistributable packages from the Microsoft web site. I installed x86 2005, x86 2010, and the two service pack 1 versions.
</p><p>If the store doesn't work, confirm 32-bit gnutls is installed.
</p>
